# Clean Code Standards (Strict)

- use arrow function only
- Prefer readability over cleverness; optimize only with measured evidence.
- Keep functions small and focused; one responsibility per function.
- Use explicit, domain-meaningful names; avoid abbreviations and generic names.
- Eliminate duplication by extracting shared logic, hooks, or utilities.
- Favor immutability and pure functions where possible.
- Handle errors intentionally: fail fast, return actionable messages, no silent catches.
- Avoid `any`, implicit coercion, and hidden side effects.
- Keep components lean: move business logic to hooks/services.
- Write code that is easy to test; isolate side effects and I/O boundaries.
- Remove dead code, commented-out code, and stale TODOs before finishing.
- avoir for loop, use forEach instead
- use object input parameter for function instead of many parameters

## Enforced Review Checks

- No function should require comments to explain obvious flow.
- No boolean prop names that are ambiguous (`flag`, `enabled` without context).
- No magic strings/numbers; extract constants with intent-revealing names.
- No deep nesting when guard clauses can flatten control flow.
- No broad exports from feature internals unless intentionally public.
